' plan-58-B rules 10, 11 and 12 — the `RETURN <expr> LENGTH <expr>` clause.
'
' Rule 10 is the load-bearing one, and it is a correctness rule rather than a
' style rule. A CBuffer's block is allocated at its full SIZE capacity; without a
' LENGTH clause the list's `count` stays at that capacity, so a callee that
' writes fewer bytes than the buffer holds leaves the remainder as uninitialized
' ARENA memory which ordinary code then reads as data.
'
' That was observed, not theorized: during plan-58-B Phase 2 a short `pread`
' surfaced stale arena bytes as the wrapper's result. Requiring LENGTH closes it
' by construction and costs nothing at runtime — which is why it was preferred
' over zero-filling the buffer, an O(N) memset paid on every call including the
' ones that fill it completely. Every real C bulk-read API reports how much it
' wrote, so there is always something to name.
LINK "demo" AS demoLink
  ' Rule 10: returns a CBuffer with no LENGTH.
  FUNC noLength(n AS Integer) AS List OF Byte
    SYMBOL "demo_read"
    ABI (buf OUT CBuffer, n CInt64) AS status CInt32
    BUFFER buf SIZE n
    RETURN buf
  END FUNC

  ' Rule 11: a LENGTH clause with no CBuffer to apply it to. A scalar result has
  ' no length to set, so this is a mistake rather than a harmless no-op.
  FUNC strayLength(n AS Integer) AS Integer
    SYMBOL "demo_count"
    ABI (n CInt64) AS status CInt32
    RETURN status LENGTH n
  END FUNC

  ' Rule 12: a LENGTH expression naming nothing real.
  FUNC badLength(n AS Integer) AS List OF Byte
    SYMBOL "demo_read2"
    ABI (buf OUT CBuffer, n CInt64) AS status CInt32
    BUFFER buf SIZE n
    RETURN buf LENGTH nosuch
  END FUNC
END LINK
